So this was an unexpected gift. I learned something new in prompting this w=
eek. I didn=E2=80=99t expect it. And I am absolutely delighted.
This is a technique that lets you quickly and easily create what are effect=
ively macro shortcuts for prompts in ChatGPT. And yes, they really work. An=
d yes, they are as simple as typing a wake string or word of some kind into=
 ChatGPT.
And that=E2=80=99s it. You don=E2=80=99t have to call the whole prompt. Cha=
tGPT just knows it.=20
And best of all it=E2=80=99s easy to use this across chats (ChatGPT does it=
 automatically) and it=E2=80=99s super easy to share this with colleagues, =
so teams can use it too. I=E2=80=99ll show you how in this post, and I prom=
ise you can do this in like 10 minutes, even if you=E2=80=99re a beginner!
Subscribers get all these posts!
How I figured this out
Dan Shipper tossed off a line on X that instantly reframed how I think abou=
t ChatGPT: =E2=80=9CYou can install prompts like programs by writing them t=
o memory.=E2=80=9D [Link [ https://substack.com/redirect/1d9f484c-200c-4b06=
-b652-23844b14f10b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiNWtiOTN6In0.zdzy88YFxPmLQJf9hshgUC7BDnPG6RxQ=
4tAjMRMPOw0 ]]=20
Yes I know you all think I know everything about ChatGPT, but I don=E2=80=
=99t. And what=E2=80=99s more interesting is nobody does. These are emergen=
t systems (video about that yesterday [ https://substack.com/redirect/62a28=
c87-1d64-4fde-9426-aec654ace87e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiNWtiOTN6In0.zdzy88YFxPmLQJf9hsh=
gUC7BDnPG6RxQ4tAjMRMPOw0 ]).
For me, until I saw Dan=E2=80=99s tweet I=E2=80=99d been mentally bracketin=
g the memory tab as a quirky place for personal trivia=E2=80=94favorite aut=
hors, timezone, whatever. It was a complete concept flip for me to think of=
 it as a prompt locker: store a micro-instruction once, summon it later wit=
h a unique wake-word, and the model applies the rule only when you ask. No =
plug-ins, no wrappers, just disciplined conversation.
What=E2=80=99s great is I could test the idea in 30 seconds: saved a five-l=
ine rule called SNACK, fired the word, and watched ChatGPT spit a perfect f=
ive-word summary on command. That tiny demo convinced me we=E2=80=99re unde=
r-using the feature=E2=80=94and over-typing ourselves to death=E2=80=94beca=
use we haven=E2=80=99t systematized how to load, name, and prune these wake=
-word =E2=80=9Cprograms.=E2=80=9D
In the rest of this piece I=E2=80=99ll show you exactly how the mechanism w=
orks, the anatomy of a durable micro-rule, and a step-by-step audit to disc=
over wake-words tailored to your own workflow.
Start in 60 seconds
Here=E2=80=99s the fastest way to feel the prompt-locker trick in your own =
hands=E2=80=94think of it as a 60-second espresso shot for skeptics.
Open a fresh ChatGPT chat and paste the five-line rule below, ending with =
=E2=80=9CPlease remember this.=E2=80=9D
Wake-word SNACK =E2=86=92 Return a five-word summary of any text that follo=
ws. Only five words, no extras.
Wait for ChatGPT to answer =E2=80=9CGot it!=E2=80=9D and tell you the memor=
y was saved. That reply is your install confirmation=E2=80=94no =E2=80=9CGo=
t it,=E2=80=9D no brick.
Fire a test with a brand new chat:
SNACK: =E2=80=9CHello, world! Today is beautiful.=E2=80=9D
The model should spit back something like: Hello world beautiful day=E2=80=
=94exactly five words, zero chatter.
You just saved an instruction once and executed it on demand, zero copy-pas=
te, zero re-explaining. I=E2=80=99m thinking of these little macros as Lego=
 bricks. That tiny demo=E2=80=94thirty seconds, tops=E2=80=94is like a memo=
ry lego brick. Name it, watch it snap into place, and click it into a conve=
rsation whenever you want it.
Next up, I=E2=80=99ll open the casing and show why the Lego brick stays qui=
et until summoned, how wake-words chain, and what keeps your normal chats f=
rom turning into accidental command storms.
How does this work?
A memory brick is essentially a system-prompt fragment you write once and m=
ount on a tripwire. Under the hood it works like this:
Tokenizer hit-check =E2=80=93 When ChatGPT receives a message, it looks at =
the very first token. If that token matches any wake-word string stored in =
your memory, the model sees the memory hit and invokes the context tokens a=
round that memory.
Silent splice =E2=80=93 Before generating a reply, the service prepends the=
 saved instruction text out of memory to its internal system prompt. Think =
of it as hot-patching the runtime: the brick=E2=80=99s rules now sit above =
anything you just typed.
One-turn scope =E2=80=93 The splice lives for exactly one completion. Becau=
se the wake-word isn=E2=80=99t re-sent on the next round, the brick=E2=80=
=99s influence disappears unless you invoke it again. That=E2=80=99s why yo=
ur everyday chats stay untouched.
When bricks beat other prompting moves
One paste per teammate, instant consistency, no plugin overhead.
Why not just stuff it in custom instructions?
Look, I think Custom Instructions are cool. I wrote about them here [ https=
://substack.com/redirect/5914498e-9eff-440c-93e8-80ba1b533b6f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiN=
WtiOTN6In0.zdzy88YFxPmLQJf9hshgUC7BDnPG6RxQ4tAjMRMPOw0 ]. But this does a d=
ifferent job. Custom Instructions persist for every chat. What I=E2=80=99m =
calling memory bricks here are persisted, free, and opt-in=E2=80=94they tri=
gger only when you want them. They=E2=80=99re the sweet spot between verbos=
e copy-paste templates and heavyweight universal instructions.
Safe limits & gotchas
Cap active bricks at a reasonable number to avoid collisions; overlapping l=
ength rules are the fastest path to garbled output.
Overwrite, don=E2=80=99t append=E2=80=94multiple versions of the same brick=
 create instruction soup.
If you=E2=80=99re nervous about accidental invocation, use a non-English st=
ring or leading symbol (:TRIM, =E2=9A=A1SPEC) to dodge accidental triggers.
Next, we=E2=80=99ll mine your own chat history to surface the instructions =
you repeat most and convert them into bricks that pay rent rather than gath=
er dust.
Discovering Your Wake-Words
Most people start by directly copying a skill to learn it. That doesn=E2=80=
=99t work well here. If you copy SNACK it will gather dust. A brick only pa=
ys rent if it automates a chore you repeat. Here=E2=80=99s a five-step audi=
t that turns personal friction into durable wake-words.
Mine your chat history (10 minutes).
Scroll the last week of conversations and look at chats where you re-typed =
an instruction=E2=80=94anything like =E2=80=9Cexplain in plain English,=E2=
=80=9D =E2=80=9Cflag assumptions,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cformat as Jira.=E2=
=80=9D My favorite is =E2=80=9Cffs stop answering in tables=E2=80=9D to o3 =
lol=E2=80=94if it shows up three times or more, drop it into a scratch pad.
Group by outcome, not wording.
Merge near-duplicates. =E2=80=9CTighten copy,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Cremove fluf=
f,=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cbe concise=E2=80=9D all collapse into a single job=
: Trim language. This pruning keeps your eventual brick list short enough t=
o remember without a cheat sheet.
Draft micro-guides in a table.
Keep each instruction atomic=E2=80=94tone or length or structure, never all=
 three. Atomic bricks click together without fighting. This is one case whe=
re long prompts don=E2=80=99t help, so don=E2=80=99t try to put a massive a=
mount of weight here.=20
